      {
        "id": 5031,
        "name": "Markus Pilman",
        "username": "markus.pilman",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/markus.pilman/{size}/379_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-09-05T22:00:08.186Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"ajbeamon\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"1611\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://sea1.discourse-cdn.com/foundationdb/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/ajbeamon/48/13_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> ajbeamon:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Would this be done through the C API, or are you recommending accessing RYWTransactions directly?</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>ah good point - RYWTransaction is just a transaction in the C API\u2026</p>\n<p>In general I would think it would be better to use the C API. And this could be implemented in any language we have bindings for.</p>\n<p>Personally I would probably implement this in flow - mostly because I think it would be much easier to test (and flow makes async programming much easier). The document layer already does something similar.</p>\n<p>So I think this boils down to taste.</p>",
